webpackJsonp([0x6d7c91bc5292],{356:function(e,A){e.exports={data:{markdownRemark:{frontmatter:{title:"The Principles of Dark Noise",date:"23 August, 2019",image:"http://media.charliemchapman.com/charlie_and_jack.JPG"},fields:{slug:"/posts/2019/8/23/dark-noise/"},html:'<p>At the beginning of this year I started working on my first indie app to release in the App Store called <a href="https://darknoise.app">Dark Noise</a>.  </p>\n<p>At first, I had a giant list of feature ideas and no idea how to distill them into a focused product. So I started by forcing myself to pick 3 principles to guide the design.</p>\n<p>I eventually landed on these core principles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Configurability</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Targeting pro users who want as many options and hooks to work the app into their workflow as possible</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Speed</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Opening app to playing sound should be as fast as possible with no compromise since this is the 99% use case</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Keep it dark</strong> (expect fat fingers)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Most users will probably be using this in a dark environment, possibly without their glasses on or half asleep.  Keep that in mind.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>After creating the principles, I took my list of feature ideas and tried to slot them all into one of those principles.  If they didn\'t fit, I tossed them in the backlog.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/dark-noise-principles-in-action-1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d-0af4d.jpg"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 750px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 130.6122448979592%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/jpeg;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;"\n        alt="Dark Noise Principles in Action"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/dark-noise-principles-in-action-1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d-5520a.jpg"\n        srcset="/static/dark-noise-principles-in-action-1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d-52dbb.jpg 188w,\n/static/dark-noise-principles-in-action-1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d-b4884.jpg 375w,\n/static/dark-noise-principles-in-action-1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d-5520a.jpg 750w,\n/static/dark-noise-principles-in-action-1696799ffa1b72e000d580b6f9576e2d-0af4d.jpg 784w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>Keeping these principles in mind as I tried to design and form an MVP was really helpful.  I have a tendency to get overly excited by an idea and drop whatever I\'m doing and build it.  Often that\'s a bad idea, but sometimes it\'s good!</p>\n<p>Whenever I had the thought of adding a bunch of custom app icons referencing podcasts I like, I realized it was something that might actually resonate with the pro users I was targeting.  And seems to have done just that!</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-link"\n    href="/static/dark-noise-app-icons-3c8c11da195a417fec74e003f81a155b-3406c.png"\n    style="display: block"\n    target="_blank"\n    rel="noopener"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class="gatsby-resp-image-wrapper"\n    style="position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 519px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"\n  >\n    <span\n      class="gatsby-resp-image-background-image"\n      style="padding-bottom: 197.3025048169557%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(\'data:image/png;base64,\'); background-size: cover; display: block;"\n    >\n      <img\n        class="gatsby-resp-image-image"\n        style="width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;"\n        alt="Dark Noise App Icons"\n        title=""\n        src="/static/dark-noise-app-icons-3c8c11da195a417fec74e003f81a155b-3406c.png"\n        srcset="/static/dark-noise-app-icons-3c8c11da195a417fec74e003f81a155b-250a1.png 188w,\n/static/dark-noise-app-icons-3c8c11da195a417fec74e003f81a155b-93180.png 375w,\n/static/dark-noise-app-icons-3c8c11da195a417fec74e003f81a155b-3406c.png 519w"\n        sizes="(max-width: 519px) 100vw, 519px"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>This also played into my pricing decisions as that market tends to prefer paying up front and is a little more averse to ads.  That\'s not to say I won\'t add a free tier in the future (in fact I probably will) but it\'s something I\'m always keeping in mind as I make these decisions.</p>\n<p>Anyway, I\'m not an expert at this, heck I\'m barely a beginner, but maybe you\'ll find my thought process interesting nonetheless.</p>\n<p><em>This post is an attempt to make a more permanent record to <a href="https://twitter.com/chuckyc17/status/1158072465739911168">this tweetstorm</a> from a few weeks ago.</em></p>',excerpt:"At the beginning of this year I started working on my first indie app to release in the App Store called  Dark Noise .   At first, I had aâ€¦"}},pathContext:{slug:"/posts/2019/8/23/dark-noise/"}}}});
